The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Frontpage | Ledo mine blast victim dies
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Ledo mine blast victim dies
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Calcutta, Nov. 9: One of the six Coal India Limited (CIL) employees injured in the first of two explosions in a Ledo colliery in Assams Tinsukia district, and admitted at Apollo Gleneagles Hospital, Calcutta, died today.         
	M. Sathyanrayana, 39, who died this morning, had sustained severe burn and blast injuries. He had sustained 75 per cent burns along with lung injuries, a doctor said at Apollo Gleneagles Hospital, where the victims were admitted.         
	Sathyanarayana was taken to the CILs hospital in Assams Margarita after the blast, which took place around 5.45am on Tuesday. He was shifted to Apollo Gleneagles Hospital in Calcutta on Friday in an unconscious and critical condition and was immediately put on life support system.        
	Bronchoscopy done on him revealed that he had suffered extensive lung injuries, a doctor said.        
	Ranjit Dutta, manager public relation of the North Eastern Coal Field, while confirming Satyanarayans death, said the company will provide an ex gratia of Rs 5 lakh to his next of kin.         
	Dutta said according to the rules of the company, a dependent of the worker would be given a job in the company.         
	Bijoy Shankar Rajbhor, 47, another victim who was brought to Apollo on Friday, is also in an extremely critical state.                     
	He has suffered 55 per cent burns along with lung injury. He is on incubator, the doctor said.        
	Four other CIL employees  G. Chalaya, 47, Radheshyam Bamon, 56, Uttam Deb, 46, and M. Nagrajoo, 41  were brought to Calcutta yesterday. All of them are still in the intensive care unit, but are stable, an official said.        
	The first explosion, termed as hot air burst by officials, occurred in Ledo colliery, operated by the North Eastern Coal Fields (NECF) of CIL, in which the victims who were brought to Calcutta for treatment were injured. Twelve more colliery workers were injured in the second explosion in Lachit coal mine on Friday.                                                                                                                                           
